00:15:23,367 --> 00:15:27,246
- Yeah, but he wasn't very good.
- Harry, put the gun down!
You're acting insane!

208
00:15:27,327 --> 00:15:29,636
Now honey, go get some clothes on
and get out of the way.

209
00:15:29,727 --> 00:15:33,640
- You can't control my life.
- Fine. Clothes. Now!

210
00:15:33,727 --> 00:15:36,958
All right, stop, all right? It was funny
for a minute, it's not funny any more.

211
00:15:40,047 --> 00:15:43,835
- Harry, this is illegal, man.
- I'm temporarily insane, Rock.
It's all right.

212
00:15:48,567 --> 00:15:50,319
- Do I look like I'm crazy to you?
- Well...

213
00:15:50,407 --> 00:15:52,477
Harry, hey, just cool down.

214
00:15:52,527 --> 00:15:55,519
- What are you... Okay, stop.
- All right. All right, Harry.

215
00:15:55,607 --> 00:15:57,757
All right. Now, listen, man to man.

216
00:15:57,807 --> 00:16:00,560
I'm serious. I love her.

217
00:16:00,647 --> 00:16:02,444
Way wrong answer.

218
00:16:05,167 --> 00:16:07,840
- Whoa, whoa, Harry. It's gettin' real.
- Harry! Come on, Harry!

219
00:16:07,927 --> 00:16:10,566
- Stop him!
- You shot him!

220
00:16:10,607 --> 00:16:12,325
Bullet never got close.
Just a ricochet.

221
00:16:12,407 --> 00:16:14,796
You know, it's all funny
till somebody gets shot in the leg.

222
00:16:14,887 --> 00:16:18,482
Hey, pucker up!
We got clients incoming!

223
00:16:19,927 --> 00:16:22,885
Uh, b-back in, uh, 1974...

224
00:16:22,967 --> 00:16:26,323
w-we first got the-the idea,
the possibility that a, that a meteor
or an asteroid...

225
00:16:26,407 --> 00:16:30,082
I need somebody who's had a little less
caffeine this morning. Doc, translate.

226
00:16:30,167 --> 00:16:33,762
Our first feasibility plan was to use
a spread-focus laser generator...

227
00:16:33,847 --> 00:16:35,724
to heat the object
to the point of fracture.

228
00:16:35,807 --> 00:16:38,002
That's like shooting a B.B. Gun
at a freight train, Doc.

229
00:16:38,087 --> 00:16:39,918
Uh, some of us have got this idea.

230
00:16:40,007 --> 00:16:43,397
We want to land a craft,
deploy solar sails.

231
00:16:43,487 --> 00:16:46,320
You'll have a great big canopy.
Solar winds will be caught...

232
00:16:46,407 --> 00:16:49,638
by these mylar sails.

233
00:16:49,727 --> 00:16:51,683
- Okay.
- Come on, guys.

234
00:16:51,767 --> 00:16:55,362
We gotta come up with something
realistic here. We got 18 days.

235
00:16:55,407 --> 00:16:58,956
That's 431 hours,
15 minutes and 18 seconds.

236
00:16:59,047 --> 00:17:01,607
Time's a luxury we don't have.
What?

237
00:17:04,487 --> 00:17:07,877
Listen, Harry. A.J. Is my choice...
my choice and not yours.

238
00:17:07,967 --> 00:17:11,676
He's the only one in your age bracket,
Grace. It's not a choice,
it's a lack of options.

239
00:17:11,727 --> 00:17:16,482
I don't know what in the world makes
you think that you have the right
to tell me what to do any more, Harry.

240
00:17:16,567 --> 00:17:18,717
I suppose being your father
doesn't count, huh?

241
00:17:18,767 --> 00:17:20,723
- Not really.
- Since when?

242
00:17:20,807 --> 00:17:23,799
Since I reached the age of 10
and became older than you, Harry.

243
00:17:23,847 --> 00:17:25,599
Since Mom split.
Why don't you take your pick?

244
00:17:25,687 --> 00:17:31,284
Look, I understand that you are
handicapped by a natural immaturity
and I forgive you.

245
00:17:31,367 --> 00:17:34,006
I may be an immature father, okay?
But I'm still your employer.

246
00:17:34,087 --> 00:17:37,159
And as your boss I want you
on that crew boat tonight
and back in the office by Monday.

247
00:17:37,247 --> 00:17:40,239
- You got that?
- Okay. I quit.

248
00:17:40,327 --> 00:17:44,366
Grace, you can't quit now.
I need you to keep on workin'.

249
00:17:46,487 --> 00:17:51,242
- Hi, Harry!
- What are you smilin' about?

250
00:17:52,607 --> 00:17:56,202
I've been seein' A.J.
For more than five months, Harry.

251
00:17:57,967 --> 00:18:00,606
You little hypocrite. I ever held you
back once from doin' anything?

252
00:18:00,647 --> 00:18:03,445
What about having a life, Harry?
The first time I got my period...

253
00:18:03,527 --> 00:18:05,677
Rockhound had to take me
into Taipei for Tampax...

254
00:18:05,767 --> 00:18:07,883
and then he had to show me
how to use 'em, Harry.

255
00:18:10,447 --> 00:18:13,962
I ju... No, l-I told her how to use it.
I didn't show her, Harry.

256
00:18:15,287 --> 00:18:18,723
I was playing
with titanium depth gauges when
I should've been playing with dolls.

257
00:18:18,807 --> 00:18:22,800
I mean, I learned about the birds and
the bees from Freddie Noonan's tattoos.

258
00:18:22,887 --> 00:18:25,606
Look, I was raised
on roughnecks by you...

259
00:18:25,687 --> 00:18:28,155
and now you get all shocked and shaken
when I fall in love with one.

260
00:18:28,247 --> 00:18:31,603
- So who is the hypocrite here,
Harry, huh? Who?
- Look at those nice pipes up there.

261
00:18:31,687 --> 00:18:35,680
- Listen to me, Grace. I want you...
- No, you listen to me, Harry.
I grew up.

262
00:18:35,767 --> 00:18:38,406
With the proximity of the asteroid...

263
00:18:38,447 --> 00:18:41,086
and no prep time,
none of our primary plans can work.

264
00:18:41,127 --> 00:18:45,325
Why don't we just send up 150 nuclear
warheads and blast that rock apart?

265
00:18:45,407 --> 00:18:48,717
- Terrible idea.
- Was I talkin' to you?

266
00:18:48,807 --> 00:18:53,722
This is Dr Ronald Quincy from research,
pretty much the smartest man on the
planet. You might want to listen to him.

267
00:18:53,767 --> 00:18:58,443
General, if you consider your target...
her composition, her dimensions...

268
00:18:58,527 --> 00:19:01,599
her sheer velocity, you could fire
every nuke you've got at her...

269
00:19:01,647 --> 00:19:04,719
and she'll just smile at you
and keep on coming.

270
00:19:04,807 --> 00:19:07,037
You should know that the president's
scientific advisors...

271
00:19:07,127 --> 00:19:11,564
are suggesting that a nuclear blast
could change this asteroid's trajectory.

272
00:19:11,647 --> 00:19:15,196
I know the president's chief scientific
advisor. We were at M.I.T. Together.

273
00:19:15,287 --> 00:19:18,245
And in a situation like this, you...
you really don't want...

274
00:19:18,287 --> 00:19:22,439
to take the advice of a man
who got a C-minus in astrophysics.

275
00:19:22,527 --> 00:19:27,396
The president's advisors are,
um, wrong. I'm right.

276
00:19:27,487 --> 00:19:29,523
Hitting the rock from the outside
won't do the job.

277
00:19:29,607 --> 00:19:32,917
Imagine a firecracker
in the palm of your hand.

278
00:19:32,967 --> 00:19:36,676
You set it off.
What happens? Burn your hand, right?

279
00:19:36,767 --> 00:19:40,282
You close your fist around
the same firecracker and set it off...

280
00:19:42,167 --> 00:19:44,761
Your wife's gonna be opening your
ketchup bottles the rest of your life.

281
00:19:44,807 --> 00:19:46,877
Are you suggesting
we blow this thing up from the inside?

282
00:19:46,927 --> 00:19:49,680
- That's exactly what I'm saying.
- How?

283
00:19:49,767 --> 00:19:53,442
We drill. We bring in the world's
best deep-core driller.

284
00:19:53,487 --> 00:19:55,921
Harry, get up here!
We're takin' a hit!

285
00:19:56,007 --> 00:19:57,963
- Get A.J. Up here! Whoa!
- Come on!

286
00:19:59,887 --> 00:20:02,082
Send another pipe on down!
Right now! Full pipe!

287
00:20:03,527 --> 00:20:07,281
- It's a gas pocket.
- I told you. Am I lucky
or am I just a genius?

288
00:20:07,367 --> 00:20:10,279
I shut it down for a reason, you
jackass! The relief valve's fried open.

289
00:20:13,127 --> 00:20:17,325
Shut off the number two valve!
Grace, get the clients outta here now!

290
00:20:23,407 --> 00:20:25,921
Chick, get 'em outta here!
Get 'em off the rig now!

291
00:20:31,247 --> 00:20:34,319
Get the hell down!
This thing is gonna blow!

292
00:20:41,527 --> 00:20:44,519
Get out! Chick, get out now!

293
00:20:44,607 --> 00:20:47,838
Get down!

294
00:20:47,887 --> 00:20:50,879
Three dozen research calls and every
time the same man is recommended.

295
00:20:50,967 --> 00:20:53,117
He's worked on every terrain
this planet can offer.

296
00:20:53,207 --> 00:20:55,277
Whenever they said it couldn't be
drilled, this guy drilled it.

297
00:20:55,367 --> 00:20:58,962
- Everybody all right?
- We struck oil, baby!

298
00:20:59,047 --> 00:21:02,403
Somebody could've got killed out here
today. You want that on your conscience?

299
00:21:04,927 --> 00:21:06,838
High thumb. You are man, Harry.

300
00:21:06,887 --> 00:21:09,526
Thumbs high.

301
00:21:12,167 --> 00:21:14,078
You're fired.

302
00:21:18,367 --> 00:21:20,722
Who's Harry Stamper?

303
00:21:20,807 --> 00:21:23,321
Yeah, I'm Harry Stamper.
What's all this about?

304
00:21:23,367 --> 00:21:26,916
Mr Stamper, I'm General Montgomery,
commander of the Pacific air forces.

305
00:21:27,007 --> 00:21:29,157
I've been sent here
by the secretary of defence...

306
00:21:29,247 --> 00:21:32,523
on direct orders from the president
of the United States.

307
00:21:32,607 --> 00:21:34,882
It's a matter of urgent
national security.

308
00:21:34,967 --> 00:21:38,357
I need you to get on that chopper
right now, no questions asked.

309
00:21:38,407 --> 00:21:41,558
- Crazy Willie put you up to this?
- Afraid I don't know Crazy Willie.

310
00:21:41,607 --> 00:21:44,644
Sir, I'm dead serious about this.

311
00:21:45,967 --> 00:21:47,685
- Harry.
- What?

312
00:21:47,727 --> 00:21:49,957
Man, I swear to God,
she never told me her age.

313
00:21:50,047 --> 00:21:52,800
It's all right.
Relax. It's about me.

314
00:21:53,807 --> 00:21:55,923
Oh. Forget it.

315
00:22:00,007 --> 00:22:02,316
All right, General.
I'll go with ya.

316
00:22:02,407 --> 00:22:05,524
On one condition...
we have to take my daughter along.

317
00:22:08,527 --> 00:22:10,483
- What did I do?
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. Where you guys
takin' her? Wait a minute.

318
00:22:10,567 --> 00:22:12,956
- Sir, stay right here.
- Well...

319
00:22:13,047 --> 00:22:15,402
Chick! Get him paid,
get him off the rig!

320
00:22:25,367 --> 00:22:28,359
- Mr Stamper?
- Yeah, I'm Harry Stamper.

321
00:22:28,447 --> 00:22:32,156
How ya doin'? Miss Stamper.
I'm Dan Truman, executive director here.

322
00:22:32,247 --> 00:22:34,715
- Now listen, on behalf of all of us,
I'd really like to apologize...
- Apologize.

323
00:22:34,807 --> 00:22:37,002
I don't know if we can take
any more apologies, Mr Truman.

324
00:22:37,087 --> 00:22:39,920
We've been apologized to
for the last 18 and a half hours.

325
00:22:40,007 --> 00:22:42,237
So if you don't mind,
how 'bout if we just get on with it...

326
00:22:42,327 --> 00:22:44,966
and you tell us why we're here
at the NASA space centre?

327
00:22:45,007 --> 00:22:49,523
- We should probably talk alone.
- Mr Truman, I don't keep any secrets
from my daughter, Grace.

328
00:22:49,607 --> 00:22:52,075
So whether you tell her now or
I tell her later she's gonna find out...

329
00:22:52,167 --> 00:22:54,442
one way or the other,
so why don't we just get on with it?

330
00:22:54,527 --> 00:22:58,679
So when the rogue comet hit the asteroid
belt, it sent shrapnel right for us.

331
00:22:58,727 --> 00:23:01,321
For the next 15 days
the Earth's in a shooting gallery.

332
00:23:01,407 --> 00:23:05,320
Even if the asteroid itself hits
the water, it's still hitting land.

333
00:23:05,407 --> 00:23:09,958
It'll flash-boil millions
of gallons of sea water and slam
into the ocean bedrock.

334
00:23:10,047 --> 00:23:13,596
Now, if it's a Pacific Ocean impact...
which we think it will be...

335
00:23:13,687 --> 00:23:17,965
it'll create a tidal wave three miles
high, travel at 1,000 miles an hour...

336
00:23:18,047 --> 00:23:21,357
covering California
and washing up in Denver.

337
00:23:21,447 --> 00:23:24,723
Japan's gone. Australia's wiped out.

338
00:23:24,807 --> 00:23:27,640
Half the world's population'll be
incinerated by the heat blast...

339
00:23:27,687 --> 00:23:30,565
and the rest'll freeze to death
from nuclear winter.

340
00:23:30,607 --> 00:23:32,484
That's unbelievable.

341
00:23:33,807 --> 00:23:36,401
Well, actually,
this is as real as it gets.

342
00:23:38,767 --> 00:23:41,565
Well, it's coming, right now...

343
00:23:41,607 --> 00:23:44,599
right for us...
at 22,000 miles an hour.

344
00:23:44,647 --> 00:23:47,445
Not a soul on Earth can hide from it.

345
00:24:02,567 --> 00:24:04,637
I take it you're not
alerting everyone like this.

346
00:24:04,727 --> 00:24:07,719
Nobody knows.
That's the way it stays.

347
00:24:07,807 --> 00:24:10,367
For the next ten days, there are
only nine telescopes in the world...

348
00:24:10,407 --> 00:24:12,967
that can spot the asteroid,
and we control eight of'em.

349
00:24:13,047 --> 00:24:15,925
The president's classified
this information top secret.

350
00:24:16,007 --> 00:24:18,680
If news like this got out,
there'd be an overnight breakdown...

351
00:24:18,727 --> 00:24:23,642
of basic social services worldwide...
rioting, mass religious hysteria.

352
00:24:23,687 --> 00:24:26,281
Total chaos. You can imagine.

353
00:24:26,367 --> 00:24:29,359
Basically the worst parts
of the Bible.

354
00:24:31,927 --> 00:24:35,078
Six billion people on the planet...

355
00:24:35,167 --> 00:24:37,158
why'd you guys call me?

356
00:24:37,247 --> 00:24:40,523
- We need you to prep the team
we're sending up.
- Up?

357
00:24:40,607 --> 00:24:43,997
We'll send 'em to the asteroid,
they'll land, they'll drill a hole,
they'll drop some nukes...

358
00:24:44,047 --> 00:24:46,880
take off and detonate
if we can fix this equipment problem.

359
00:24:46,927 --> 00:24:51,523
Now, the, uh, drilling unit's
a prototype we've been building
for the Mars project.

360
00:24:51,567 --> 00:24:55,037
You, uh...
you might recognize the rig.

361
00:24:56,047 --> 00:24:59,676
Yeah, well, I guess I should
recognize it. It's my design.

362
00:25:02,287 --> 00:25:04,562
What'd you do?
Steal a key to the patent office?

363
00:25:04,647 --> 00:25:07,480
- Yeah, basically.
- Let me get this straight.

364
00:25:07,527 --> 00:25:11,679
I got pulled off an oil rig,
flown halfway around the world
because you stole my drill design...

365
00:25:11,727 --> 00:25:15,242
couldn't read the plans right
and did a piss-poor job
of putting it together, is that it?

366
00:25:15,327 --> 00:25:18,080
- Well, technically,
patents don't apply to outer space.
- Just shut up, Quincy.

367
00:25:18,127 --> 00:25:21,437
It's not going to Mars any more.
It's going to try to save this planet.

368
00:25:21,487 --> 00:25:23,523
And we need to know
what's wrong with it pretty quick.

369
00:25:23,567 --> 00:25:25,523
You said we did a bad job
of putting it together?

370
00:25:25,607 --> 00:25:28,883
No, I said you did a piss-poor job
of putting it together.

371
00:25:28,967 --> 00:25:31,037
First of all, you got
the flow system all reversed.

372
00:25:31,087 --> 00:25:35,319
Let me guess: You've been tearin' up
rotors and you can't figure out why.

373
00:25:35,367 --> 00:25:39,201
- Yeah, that's right, actually.
- Well, that's because your cams
are all wrong, Mr Wizard.

374
00:25:39,247 --> 00:25:43,035
- Who's been operating this thing?
- Right there.

375
00:25:43,087 --> 00:25:46,159
W-We've actually... we've had them
training for eight months solid now.

376
00:25:46,247 --> 00:25:48,966
- Eight whole months?
- Well, pretty much, yeah.

377
00:25:49,047 --> 00:25:52,357
- Well, gee whiz.
- Well, this is the team
that has to do the job up there.

378
00:25:52,447 --> 00:25:54,403
We need you to train 'em down here.

379
00:25:54,447 --> 00:25:56,483
Well, Mr Stamper, what do you think?

380
00:25:56,567 --> 00:25:59,206
You know, drilling's a science.
It's an art.

381
00:25:59,247 --> 00:26:01,442
I'm a third-generation driller,
doin' it all my life...

382
00:26:01,527 --> 00:26:03,995
and I still haven't got it
all figured out.

383
00:26:04,087 --> 00:26:07,397
I assume you sent for me because
somebody told you I was the best.

384
00:26:07,487 --> 00:26:09,955
Well, I'm only the best
because I work with the best.

385
00:26:10,047 --> 00:26:13,596
You don't trust the men you're
working with, you're as good as dead.

386
00:26:13,687 --> 00:26:15,757
Now, you want to send
these boys into space, fine.

387
00:26:15,847 --> 00:26:17,838
I'm sure they'll make
good astronauts.

388
00:26:17,927 --> 00:26:20,441
But they don't know jack
about drillin'.

389
00:26:20,487 --> 00:26:23,081
- What's your contingency plan?
- Contingency plan?

390
00:26:23,167 --> 00:26:25,840
Your backup plan. You gotta have
some kind of backup plan, right?

391
00:26:25,927 --> 00:26:28,839
- No, we don't have a backup plan.
This is it.
- And this is the best that you could...

392
00:26:28,927 --> 00:26:32,442
that the-the government,
the U.S. Government can come up with?

393
00:26:32,487 --> 00:26:35,684
I mean, y-you're NASA, for cryin'
out loud. You put a man on the moon.

394
00:26:35,767 --> 00:26:38,918
You're geniuses! Y-You're the guys
that think this shit up.

395
00:26:39,007 --> 00:26:41,362
I'm sure you got a team of men
sittin' around somewhere right now...

396
00:26:41,447 --> 00:26:43,722
just thinkin' shit up
and somebody backin' them up.

397
00:26:43,807 --> 00:26:46,446
You tellin' me you don't have
a backup plan, that these
eight Boy Scouts right here...

398
00:26:46,527 --> 00:26:49,325
that is the world's hope,
that's what you're tellin' me?

399
00:26:49,407 --> 00:26:52,479
- Yeah.
- Oh, Jesus. Damn it.

400
00:26:53,607 --> 00:26:56,963
We're a little short on time here.
Will you help us?

401
00:27:01,167 --> 00:27:04,045
- All they gotta do is drill?
- That's it.

402
00:27:04,127 --> 00:27:06,561
No spacewalkin',
no crazy astronaut stuff?

403
00:27:06,607 --> 00:27:09,326
Just drill.

404
00:27:09,407 --> 00:27:11,796
How many men were you plannin'
on takin' up there?

405
00:27:11,847 --> 00:27:13,803
We're sendin' up
two shuttles, two teams.

406
00:27:13,887 --> 00:27:16,037
If I do this,
I'm gonna wanna take my own men.

407
00:27:16,127 --> 00:27:18,163
You got it.

408
00:27:18,247 --> 00:27:21,125
So you're saying you'll help us?

409
00:27:21,207 --> 00:27:23,004
Yes, sir.

410
00:27:23,047 --> 00:27:25,117
Thanks.

411
00:27:30,887 --> 00:27:33,685
I just don't trust anybody else
to do it, that's all.

412
00:27:36,887 --> 00:27:39,526
No, Mrs Curlene,
it's Harry Stamper.

413
00:27:39,567 --> 00:27:43,242
If you see Bear, you tell him
Harry's lookin' for him.

414
00:27:43,327 --> 00:27:46,797
Those guys get off this rig,
they scatter.J. Otis Curlene Bear...

415
00:27:46,887 --> 00:27:50,721
probably the only black man
on a big hog in Kadoka, South Dakota.

416
00:27:50,767 --> 00:27:53,201
Come and get Papa Bear!

417
00:27:55,367 --> 00:27:58,325
- Uh, Max.
- You got a weight limit on the shuttle?

418
00:28:00,287 --> 00:28:02,403
- Max.
- Hey, Mama.

